            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.12.52" />
                <note type="curatorial">97 House Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">52</fw>
                <fw type="letterhead">
Editorial Department            ST. LOUIS POST-DISPATCH     
<lb/>
                ST. LOUIS, MO.
                </fw>
<opener>
    <dateline>Nov. 5, 1927.</dateline>

<salute>Dear Comrade:</salute>
</opener>
<p>I have just gotten back from lecturing at Topeka and Wichita. Big crowds and find response. It was easy. I am impressed more than ever with <add>the</add> great possibilities for pushing the CYCLE in the schools. Between the Mississippi and the Rockies one hundred thousand could be sold easily, if anything at all were done about it. I do wish we could look forward to a part-year connection with Macmillans for you. Does this seem impossible to you now? Yes, your <add>ex-</add>governor would be of great value on our board, which already shows some great names, notably David Starr Jordan, Clarence Darrow, Richard Burton, etc. I'm in a hurry this morning and can't write more.</p>
<closer>
<salute>With endless love,</salute>

<signed>Jno</signed>
</closer>
<postscript><p>I could almost make a living from lecture engagements that are <hi rend="underline">offered me.</hi></p></postscript>

</div1>
</body>
    
